Japanese media reports indicate Japan's intention to nearly double its annual catch of Minke whales in the Antarctic, currently set at 440, and to hunt endangered humpback and fin whales.
Australia strongly opposes this move but refrains from boarding Japanese whaling ships to avoid accusations of piracy.
Prime Minister Howard and Attorney General Ruddock emphasize their opposition to Japan's whaling practices, advocating for non-lethal research methods.
Despite diplomatic efforts, Japan remains firm in its pursuit of expanding its whale cull, prompting international backlash and legal challenges.
The ongoing debate at the International Whaling Commission highlights the contentious issue of whaling for scientific purposes.
